    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1967-06-15T13:57:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1967-06-15T13:57:00-05:00" n="173"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d173">
                <head>173. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Embassy in Tunisia</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d173fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, <gloss target="#t_POL1">POL</gloss> 27 ARAB–ISR. Confidential;
                        Immediate; Limdis. Drafted by Sacksteder and <persName corresp="#p_PJAII1"
                            >Palmer</persName> (text revised in the White House); cleared by Battle,
                            <persName corresp="#p_SHHH1">Harold Saunders</persName>, and <persName
                            corresp="#p_REVD1">Eugene V. Rostow</persName>; and approved by Herbert
                        B. Thompson of <gloss target="#t_SS1">S/S</gloss>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1967-06-15T14:57:00-04:00">June 15, 1967, 2:57 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>211328. Ref: Tunis 4774, State 209980.<note n="2" xml:id="d173fn2">Both dated
                        June 9. (Ibid.) Telegram 4774 transmitted a letter from President Bourguiba
                        to President Johnson.</note>
                </p>
                <p>1. Please deliver the following message, dated June 15, 1967 from the President
                    to President Bourguiba: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“Dear Mr. President:</p>
                        <p>I fully understand the deep concern expressed in your urgent message of
                            June 9. As you know, we had tried hard to prevent war. Once it started,
                            we energetically supported the efforts of the United Nations Security
                            Council to achieve an effective cease-fire as a prelude to a lasting
                            peace.</p>
                        <p>As we attempt to mend the torn fabric of relations in the Middle East,
                            your prestige as an advocate of moderation and your consistent <pb
                                facs="0312" n="264" xml:id="pg_264"/> support of peaceful solutions
                            to international problems give you an important voice which must be
                            heard.</p>
                        <p>I am pleased to hear from your son that you continue to regain your
                            strength. I deeply appreciate the message of friendship and
                            understanding which he brought to Secretary <persName corresp="#p_RD3"
                                >Rusk</persName> and to my Special Assistant, Mr.
                                <persName>Rostow</persName>.</p>
                        <p>With my warmest personal sentiments,</p>
                        <p>
                            <persName corresp="#p_JLB1">Lyndon B. Johnson</persName>”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RD3">
                            <hi rend="strong">Rusk</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
